{
  "text": "Cervical disc herniation has been classified into central, para-central, posterolateral and lateral types [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . One study reported a review of 745 cases of disc lesions, out of which lateral disc accounted for 607 (82%, soft type) and 95 (13%, hard type) of the cases, central spondylosis for 32 (4.3%), and central soft disc herniation for eight (1.0%) [CITATION_4] . In a follow-up study involving surgical patients, data were reported from 296 cases: 246 (83%) from lateral soft and hard discs, 39 (13.2%) from spondylosis, and 11 (3.7%) from central/para-central soft discs [CITATION_5] . Of those 11, there were seven cases of central and four cases of para-central herniation [CITATION_6] . Other studies have reported greater numbers of para-central than posterolateral cases: from eight cases, five were para-central and three were posterolateral [CITATION_7] , and from 34 cases, 22 were paracentral and 12 were posterolateral [CITATION_8] . While the results from our study explain the posterolateral mechanism, other loading modes, such as flexion-extension may have to be considered to explain the para-central mechanism.",
